title: For Sale:  Mosin Nagant 91/30 All Original w/accessories
postcontent:
Like the title says, this is a Mosin Nagant 91/30 in all original condition will all the accessories (sling, dog collars, tool kit and cleaning rod, and oiling bottle). Sorry, no bayonet (got lost in the move from Virginia).


It's in magnificent condition.  As it is, I've only personally fired around 60 shots through it.  Besides removing the cosmolene and cleaning it after shooting, I haven't tampered with it at all.  I was going to have this as a project gun, turning it into a decent long range shooter by adding a scope and turning the bolt handle, but I've realized that I don't have the know-how to do it myself, and I don't know anyone with whom I would trust enough to mess with a gun that I will be shooting. 


Anyhow, there is lots that you could do with this gun.  Plenty of people sporterize these, add an aftermarket trigger, and attach a scope and bipod (some even cut the barrel), others keep it original as it was a military service rifle.  The bore is clean without any pitting, and the bolt is in pretty awesome condition as well.  The trigger pulls clean and consistent (don't have a load meter to test the lbs of pull), and the sear has a nice sharp edge that keeps the bolt in place even with being banged around.  The rear sight notch is not worn down, it also has the smaller distance increments, and the front sight post is straight and sharp, so you get a great sight picture.  It has what seems to be matching serial numbers in the reciever, bolt, and ammunition tray.


I am looking to sell this for $175 but I would be willing to trade for a bolt action rifle that fires .308 (Remington 700/ Weatherby Vanguard/ Savage 99... you get the picture) or a 12 gauge shotgun (Remington 870 express or Mossberg 500).


Thanks for looking! Hope to hear from you soon!


Forgot to mention, it's built in 1943, probably shot at some Nazis...

title: For Sale:  1866 Springfield 2nd Allin Conversion "Trapdoor" .50-70
postcontent: For Sale: For sale I have an 1866 Springfield Arsenal 2nd Allin Conversion trapdoor rifle. These rifles are historically significant as they signify the first breech loading rifles adopted by the US thus making the Cap and Ball musket obsolete. These firearms are fairly scarce as only about 12,000 1864 muskets were converted to the Allin breach loading system. Lock is clearly dated 1864 while breech is dated 1866. This one is all original and in great shape for being close to 150 years old. Metal is in good condition with no pitting or rust and wood is in excellent shape with no cracks and minimal dings and dents. Stock also retains 2 visiable inspectors cartouches as well as a third that is visable but hard to make out. Bore condition is well above average for this type of rifle retaining strong rifling and minimal pitting and still shines fairly well. I have shot this rifle with black powder .50-70 ammo manufactured by Dixie gun works and everything worked as it should even the auto ejector that usually lacks the spring in these early conversion models is present and works properly ejecting the shell out of the chamber with ease. Will consider partial cash/trades for other firearms and am particularly looking for AK 47s and similar type weapons but would like at least $400 cash included In a trade deal. May consider a full trade if deal is enticing enough. Own a true piece of American History and something that has definately seen Civil War use. E-mail, call, or text REDACTED.

This rifle is a John Bidine .54 cal. rolling block, they do not make the .54 cal. anymore, only a .50, and this one has a steel butt plate, with the engraved receiver on both sides and the heavy hammer.

title: For Sale:  AK-74
postcontent:
Brand New; Never been fired; Black synthetic stock, comes with one magazine, side mount and red dot. Please do not ask if I still have rifle. I will take the add down when it is sold.

Questions from buyers; "Can you tell me more about the rifle?"

Answers; The rifle is made by century arms. Here is a link to there web page. You can call them up. Talk to them. You can look up reviews. Century arms makes millions of guns and the rifle that I have for sale is one of them. I have never fired it before. All of the mechanics of the rifle are tight. Nothing is loose and the barrel looks good. The Ak-74 that I have for my personal use shoots just fine. The reason I have the red dot on the rifle is because the Ak-74's have short iron sights and I think the red dot makes them shoot better. No! I know the red dot makes them shoot better. Problem solved. What I have found to work the best is to sight the red dot in at 100 yards with the target just above the dot. This way the dot does not cover the target and I think you will find the Ak to be very accurate all the way up to 300 yards. You will find that at 300 yards you will be hitting just below the dot on your red dot but of course you can sight it in any way you see fit. Other than that you just have to make sure when you take the side mount on and off. That when you put the side mount back on make sure it is all the way forward or it will not zero out. The side mount is quick release so if you ever have problems with it say like batteries die. Then it quickly comes off and you can use iron sights. Hope this helps you.
